{
  "text": "In a study in a recent issue of Arthritis Research & Th erapy, Yoshimoto and colleagues [CITATION_1] demonstrate that peri pheral monocytes from patients with Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome (SS) produce signifi cantly higher amounts of the cytokines B cell-activating factor (BAFF) (also called B-lympho cyte stimulator, or BlyS) and interleukin-6 (IL-6) in compari son with normal monocytes. Increased expression of BAFF might explain pathogenic B-cell activation in several systemic autoimmune diseases (reviewed in [CITATION_2] ). Interestingly, autoreactive B cells depend more on BAFF for survival than do alloreactive B cells. BAFF involvement in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases is well illustrated in BAFF-transgenic mice, which exhibit an autoimmune disease mimicking systemic lupus erythemato sus (SLE) and primary Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome (pSS) as well as a twofold increase in frequency of B-cell lymphoma [CITATION_3] . In humans, an increased serum level of BAFF was reported in diff erent autoimmune diseases, and fi ndings concerning SLE and pSS were more consistent (reviewed in [CITATION_4] ).",
